!! Parallel Proverbs:

; 覆水难收 (fù shuǐ nán shōu)
: "Spilt water is hard to recover" - There’s no use crying over spilt milk.

; 捷足先登 (jié zú xiān dēng)
: "A fast foot is first to climb" - The early bird gets the worm.

; 同病相怜 (tóngbìngxiānglián) 
: "Patients with similar conditions empathize with each other" - Misery loves company.

; 船到桥头自然直 (chuán dào qiáotóu zì rán zhí) 
: "The ship will reach the end of the bridge in due course" - We’ll cross that bridge when we come to it.

; 皇天不负苦心人 (huángtiān bù fù kǔxīn rén)
: "Heaven won’t betray people who try their best" - Heaven helps those who help themselves.

; 善有善报，恶有恶报 (shànyǒushànbào, èyǒu’èbào)
: "Kind deeds pay rich dividends, evil is repaid with evil" - What goes around, comes around.

; 种瓜得瓜 (zhòngguādéguā)
: "As you sow a melon, so you shall reap one" - You reap what you sow.

; 媳妇熬成婆 (xífù áo chéng pó)
: "A daughter-in-law who suffers will one day become a mother-in-law." 

; 有其父必有其子 (yǒu qí fù bì yǒu qí zǐ)
: "The son is like his father" - Like father, like son.

; 患难见真情 (huànnàn jiàn zhēnqíng)
: "In adversity, true feelings are revealed" - A friend in need is a friend indeed.

; 不入虎穴，焉得虎子 (bù rù hǔxuè, yāndé hǔ zǐ)
: "If you don’t enter the tiger’s den, how will you get the tiger’s cub?" - No pain, no gain; nothing ventured, nothing gained.

; 今日事，今日毕 (jīnrì shì, jīnrì bì)
: "Today’s task, today’s job to complete" - Don’t put off until tomorrow what can be done today.

; 求人不如求己 (qiúrén bùrú qiújǐ) 
: "It’s better to rely on yourself than on the help of others" - If you want something done well, do it yourself.

; 一朝被蛇咬，十年怕井绳 (yī zhāo bèi shé yǎo, shí nián pà jǐng shéng)
: "Bitten by a snake on one morning, afraid of the rope by the well for ten years" - Once bitten, twice shy.

; 人无千日好，花无百日红 (rén wú qiān rì hǎo, huā wú bǎi rì hóng)
: "There is no person that has 1000 good days in a row, and no flower that stays red for 100 days" - All good things come to an end.

; 入乡随俗 (rù xiāng suí sú)
: "When entering a village, follow its customs" - When in Rome, do as the Romans do.

; 屋漏偏逢连夜雨 (wū lòu piān féng lián yè yǔ)
: "When the roof is leaking, that’s when you get several continuous nights of rain" - When it rains, it pours.

; 一波未平，一波又起 (yī bō wèi píng yī bō yòu qǐ) 
: "Just as one wave subsides, another one comes."

; 三个臭皮匠，胜过诸葛亮 (sān ge chòupíjiàng, shèng guò Zhūgé Liàng)
: "Three unskilled cobblers are superior to one Zhuge Liang 37" - Two heads are better than one.

; 三十年河东，三十年河西 (sān shí nián hé dōng, sān shí nián hé xī)
: "Thirty years on the east side of the river, thirty years on the west side of the river" - Easy come, easy go.

; 山不转路转 (shān bù zhuǎn lù zhuǎn) 
: "A mountain cannot turn, but a road can" - There’s more than one way to skin a cat.

; 熟能生巧 (shú néng shēng qiǎo)
: "Experience can give way to skill" - Practice makes perfect.

; 冰冻三尺，非一日之寒 (bīng dòng sān chǐ, fēi yī rì zhī hán)
: "Three feet of ice is not the result of one cold day" - Rome wasn’t built in a day [literally: 罗马不是一日建成的 (Luómǎ bù shì yī rì jiàn chéng de)].

; 饥不择食 (jībùzéshí)
: "The starving can’t choose their meals" - Beggars can’t be choosers.

; 说曹操，曹操到 (shuō Cáo Cāo, Cáo Cāo dào) 
: "Speak of Cao Cao 32 and he arrives" - Speak of the devil and he shall appear.

; 万事起头难 (wànshì qǐtóu nán) 
: "The first step in a thousand different matters is always difficult" - The first step is the hardest.

; 物以类聚 (wù yǐ lèijù)
: "Similar things are categorized together" - Birds of a feather flock together.

; 一分钱，一分货 (yī fēn qián, yī fēn huò)
: "Ten yuan of money, ten yuan of goods" - You get what you pay for.

; 英雄所见略同 (yīngxióng suǒjiànlüètóng)
: "The views of heroes are roughly alike" - Great minds think alike.

; 光阴似箭 (guāngyīn sì jiàn)
: "Time is like an arrow" - How time flies!

; 百闻不如一见 (bǎi wén bùrú yī jiàn)
: "Hearing something one hundred times is not as good as seeing it once" - Seeing is believing.

; 塞翁失马，焉知非福 (sàiwēngshīmǎ, yān zhī fēi fú)
: "When the old man from the frontier lost his horse, how could one have known that it would not be fortuitous?" - Every cloud has a silver lining.

; 钱可通神 (qiánkětōngshén) or 钱能通神 (qiánnéngtōngshén)
: "Money is divine"

; 金钱万能 (jīnqián wànnéng)
: "Money is almighty"

; 有钱能使鬼推磨 (yǒu qián néng shǐ guǐ tuīmó) 
: "If you have money you can ask for favours" - Money talks.

; 情人眼里出西施 (qíngrén yǎnlǐ chū Xī Shī)
: "In the eyes of a lover, Xi Shi 13 appears" - Beauty is in the eye of the beholder.


